# Dysarthric Speech Severity Classification 🎙️🧠

> A machine learning pipeline for classifying dysarthric speech as **Mild, Moderate, or Severe** using acoustic features (MFCCs, ZCR, Spectral Centroid) and comparing Support Vector Machine (SVM) and Random Forest classifiers.

---

## 📖 Overview

Dysarthria is a motor speech disorder caused by neurological conditions such as cerebral palsy, ALS, and Parkinson's disease, which weakens the muscles used for speech. In clinical settings, patients are categorised by severity based on intelligibility and articulation control.

This project implements an **end-to-end speech processing and classification pipeline** that:
- Generates and visualises synthetic speech samples with controllable dysarthric characteristics (jitter, shimmer, noise).
- Extracts core acoustic features natively used in clinical speech pathology.
- Trains, evaluates, and compares standard machine learning classifiers.
- Bridges foundational signal processing with real-world clinical research (e.g., the TORGO database).

---

## 📊 Visualising the Audio Data

To understand the acoustic degradation across severity classes, we analyze both the raw waveforms and their corresponding Mel-spectrograms.

### Waveforms (Amplitude vs. Time)
*As severity progresses from mild to severe, notice the distinct increase in amplitude variance, background noise, and structural breakdown.*
![Waveforms](images/waveforms.png)

### Mel-Spectrograms (Frequency vs. Time)
*The harmonic structure (the clear horizontal bands) becomes progressively degraded, blurred, and less distinct in moderate and severe cases.*
![Spectrograms](images/spectrograms.png)

---

## ⚙️ Processing Pipeline

```text
Raw Audio (.wav)
      │
      ▼  (librosa)
Feature Extraction
  ├── MFCCs (13 coefficients) — Models the vocal tract spectral envelope
  ├── Zero Crossing Rate      — Captures voicing / breathiness
  └── Spectral Centroid       — Acts as a pitch brightness proxy
      │
      ▼  (scikit-learn)
Classification Models
  ├── SVM (RBF kernel, C=10, gamma='scale')
  ├── Random Forest (100 trees)
      │
      ▼
Evaluation & Validation
  ├── 5-Fold Stratified Cross-Validation
  ├── Hold-out Test Accuracy (30% split)
  └── Confusion Matrix Analysis# Dysarthric Speech Severity Classification 🎙️🧠

